hat environment block.","pos":[8529,8856],"source":"Typically, in a desktop app, your Profiler UI prompts a startup load of your Profiler DLL by initializing an environment block that contains the required CLR Profiling API environment variables (i.e., `COR_PROFILER`, `COR_ENABLE_PROFILING`, and `COR_PROFILER_PATH`), and then creating a new process with that environment block."},{"content":"The same holds true for Windows Store apps, but the mechanisms are different.","pos":[8857,8934]},{"pos":[8936,8958],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Don’t run elevated<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>","source":"**Don’t run elevated**"},{"content":"If Process A attempts to spawn Windows Store app Process B, Process A should be run at medium integrity level, not at high integrity level (that is, not elevated).","pos":[8960,9123]},{"content":"This means that either your Profiler UI should be running at medium integrity level, or it must spawn another desktop process at medium integrity level to take care of launching the Windows Store app.","pos":[9124,9324]},{"pos":[9326,9369],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Choosing a Windows Store App to profile<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>","source":"**Choosing a Windows Store App to profile**"},{"content":"First, you’ll want to ask your profiler user which Windows Store app to launch.","pos":[9371,9450]},{"content":"For desktop apps, perhaps you’d show a file Browse dialog, and the user would find and select an .exe file.","pos":[9451,9558]},{"content":"But Windows Store apps are different, and using a Browse dialog doesn’t make sense.","pos":[9559,9642]},{"content":"Instead, it’s better to show the user a list of Windows Store apps installed for that user to select from.","pos":[9643,9749]},{"content":"You can use the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:Windows.Management.Deployment.PackageManager&gt;</ph> class to generate this list.","pos":[9751,9847],"source":"You can use the <xref:Windows.Management.Deployment.PackageManager> class to generate this list."},{"content":"<ph id=\"ph1\">`PackageManager`</ph> is a Windows Runtime class that is available to desktop apps, and in fact it is <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>only<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> available to desktop apps.","pos":[9848,9978],"source":"`PackageManager` is a Windows Runtime class that is available to desktop apps, and in fact it is *only* available to desktop apps."},{"pos":[9980,10131],"content":"The following code example from a hypothetical Profiler UI written as a desktop app in C# uses the <ph id=\"ph1\">`PackageManager`</ph> to generate a list of Windows apps:","source":"The following code example from a hypothetical Profiler UI written as a desktop app in C# uses the `PackageManager` to generate a list of Windows apps:"},{"pos":[10417,10460],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Specifying the custom environment block<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>","source":"**Specifying the custom environment block**"},{"content":"A new COM interface, <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>IPackageDebugSettings<ept id=\"p1\">](/windows/desktop/api/shobjidl_core/nn-shobjidl_core-ipackagedebugsettings)</ept>, allows you to customize the execution behavior of a Windows Store app to make some forms of diagnostics easier.","pos":[10462,10694],"source":"A new COM interface, [IPackageDebugSettings](/windows/desktop/api/shobjidl_core/nn-shobjidl_core-ipackagedebugsettings), allows you to customize the execution behavior of a Windows Store app to make some forms of diagnostics easier."},{"content":"One of its methods, <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>EnableDebugging<ept id=\"p1\">](/windows/desktop/api/shobjidl_core/nf-shobjidl_core-ipackagedebugsettings-enabledebugging)</ept>, lets you pass an environment block to the Windows Store app when it’s launched, along with other useful effects like disabling automatic process suspension.","pos":[10695,10981],"source":" One of its methods, [EnableDebugging](/windows/desktop/api/shobjidl_core/nf-shobjidl_core-ipackagedebugsettings-enabledebugging), lets you pass an environment block to the Windows Store app when it’s launched, along with other useful effects like disabling automatic process suspension."},{"content":"The environment block is important because that’s where you need to specify the environment variables (<ph id=\"ph1\">`COR_PROFILER`</ph>, <ph id=\"ph2\">`COR_ENABLE_PROFILING`</ph>, and <ph id=\"ph3\">`COR_PROFILER_PATH)`</ph>) used by the CLR to load your Profiler DLL .","pos":[10982,11194],"source":" The environment block is important because that’s where you need to specify the environment variables (`COR_PROFILER`, `COR_ENABLE_PROFILING`, and `COR_PROFILER_PATH)`) used by the CLR to load your Profiler DLL ."},{"content":"Consider the following code snippet:","pos":[11196,11232]},{"content":"There are a couple of items you'll need to get right:","pos":[11484,11537]},{"pos":[11541,11646],"content":"<ph id=\"ph1\">`packageFullName`</ph> can be determined while iterating over the packages and grabbing <ph id=\"ph2\">`package.Id.FullName`</ph>.","source":"`packageFullName` can be determined while iterating over the packages and grabbing `package.Id.FullName`."},{"content":"<ph id=\"ph1\">`debuggerCommandLine`</ph> is a bit more interesting.","pos":[11650,11698],"source":"`debuggerCommandLine` is a bit more interesting."},{"content":"In order to pass the custom environment block to the Windows Store app, you need to write your own, simplistic dummy debugger.","pos":[11699,11825]},{"content":"Windows spawns the Windows Store app suspended and then attaches your debugger by launching your debugger with a command line like in this example:","pos":[11826,11973]},{"content":"where <ph id=\"ph1\">`-p 1336`</ph> means the Windows Store app has Process ID 1336, and <ph id=\"ph2\">`-tid 1424`</ph> means Thread ID 1424 is the thread that is suspended.","pos":[12045,12179],"source":"where `-p 1336` means the Windows Store app has Process ID 1336, and `-tid 1424` means Thread ID 1424 is the thread that is suspended."},{"content":"Your dummy debugger