32,13532]},{"content":"And that means you’ll need to do a little digging through the manifest.","pos":[13533,13604]},{"pos":[13606,13831],"content":"While iterating over your packages (see \"Choosing a Windows Store App to Profile\" in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Startup load<ept id=\"p1\">](#startup-load)</ept> section earlier), you’ll want to grab the set of applications contained in the current package’s manifest:","source":"While iterating over your packages (see \"Choosing a Windows Store App to Profile\" in the [Startup load](#startup-load) section earlier), you’ll want to grab the set of applications contained in the current package’s manifest:"},{"content":"Yes, one package can have multiple applications, and each application has its own Application User Model ID.","pos":[14464,14572]},{"content":"So you’ll want to ask your user which application to profile, and grab the Application User Model ID from that particular application:","pos":[14573,14707]},{"content":"Finally, you now have what you need to launch the Windows Store app:","pos":[14887,14955]},{"pos":[15154,15191],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Remember to call DisableDebugging<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>","source":"**Remember to call DisableDebugging**"},{"pos":[15193,15614],"content":"When you called <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>IPackageDebugSettings::EnableDebugging<ept id=\"p1\">](/windows/desktop/api/shobjidl_core/nf-shobjidl_core-ipackagedebugsettings-enabledebugging)</ept>, you made a promise that you would clean up after yourself by calling the <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>IPackageDebugSettings::DisableDebugging<ept id=\"p2\">](/windows/desktop/api/shobjidl_core/nf-shobjidl_core-ipackagedebugsettings-disabledebugging)</ept> method, so be sure to do that when the profiling session is over.","source":"When you called [IPackageDebugSettings::EnableDebugging](/windows/desktop/api/shobjidl_core/nf-shobjidl_core-ipackagedebugsettings-enabledebugging), you made a promise that you would clean up after yourself by calling the [IPackageDebugSettings::DisableDebugging](/windows/desktop/api/shobjidl_core/nf-shobjidl_core-ipackagedebugsettings-disabledebugging) method, so be sure to do that when the profiling session is over."},{"pos":[15620,15631],"content":"Attach load","linkify":"Attach load","nodes":[{"content":"Attach load","pos":[0,11]}]},{"content":"When your Profiler UI wants to attach its Profiler DLL to an application that has already started running, it uses <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>ICLRProfiling::AttachProfiler<ept id=\"p1\">](iclrprofiling-attachprofiler-method.md)</ept>.","pos":[15633,15820],"source":"When your Profiler UI wants to attach its Profiler DLL to an application that has already started running, it uses [ICLRProfiling::AttachProfiler](iclrprofiling-attachprofiler-method.md)."},{"content":"The same holds true with Windows Store apps.","pos":[15821,15865]},{"content":"But in addition to the common considerations listed earlier, make sure the that the target Windows Store app is not suspended.","pos":[15866,15992]},{"pos":[15994,16013],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>EnableDebugging<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>","source":"**EnableDebugging**"},{"content":"As with startup load, call the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>IPackageDebugSettings::EnableDebugging<ept id=\"p1\">](/windows/desktop/api/shobjidl_core/nf-shobjidl_core-ipackagedebugsettings-enabledebugging)</ept> method.","pos":[16015,16185],"source":"As with startup load, call the [IPackageDebugSettings::EnableDebugging](/windows/desktop/api/shobjidl_core/nf-shobjidl_core-ipackagedebugsettings-enabledebugging) method."},{"content":"You don’t need it for passing an environment block, but you need one of its other features: disabling automatic process suspension.","pos":[16186,16317]},{"content":"Otherwise, when your Profiler UI calls <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>AttachProfiler<ept id=\"p1\">](iclrprofiling-attachprofiler-method.md)</ept>, the target Windows Store app may be suspended.","pos":[16318,16461],"source":" Otherwise, when your Profiler UI calls [AttachProfiler](iclrprofiling-attachprofiler-method.md), the target Windows Store app may be suspended."},{"content":"In fact, this is likely if the user is now interacting with your Profiler UI, and the Windows Store app is not active on any of the user’s screens.","pos":[16462,16609]},{"content":"And if the Windows Store app is suspended, it won’t be able to respond to any signal that the CLR sends to it to attach your Profiler DLL.","pos":[16610,16748]},{"content":"So you’ll want to do something like this:","pos":[16750,16791]},{"content":"This is the same call you’d make for the startup load case, except you don’t specify a debugger command line or an environment block.","pos":[17056,17189]},{"pos":[17191,17211],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>DisableDebugging<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>","source":"**DisableDebugging**"},{"pos":[17213,17420],"content":"As always, don’t forget to call <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>IPackageDebugSettings::DisableDebugging<ept id=\"p1\">](/windows/desktop/api/shobjidl_core/nf-shobjidl_core-ipackagedebugsettings-disabledebugging)</ept> when your profiling session is completed.","source":"As always, don’t forget to call [IPackageDebugSettings::DisableDebugging](/windows/desktop/api/shobjidl_core/nf-shobjidl_core-ipackagedebugsettings-disabledebugging) when your profiling session is completed."},{"pos":[17425,17461],"content":"Running inside the Windows Store app","linkify":"Running inside the Windows Store app","nodes":[{"content":"Running inside the Windows Store app","pos":[0,36]}]},{"content":"So the Windows Store app has finally loaded your Profiler DLL.","pos":[17463,17525]},{"content":"Now your Profiler DLL must be taught how to play by the different rules required by Windows Store apps, including which APIs are allowable and how to run with reduced permissions.","pos":[17526,17705]},{"pos":[17711,17746],"content":"Stick to the Windows Store app APIs","linkify":"Stick to the Windows Store app APIs","nodes":[{"content":"Stick to the Windows Store app APIs","pos":[0,35]}]},{"content":"As you browse the Windows API, you’ll notice that every API is documented as being applicable to desktop apps, Windows Store apps, or both.","pos":[17748,17887]},{"content":"For example, the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Requirements<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> section of the documentation for the <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>InitializeCriticalSectionAndSpinCount<ept id=\"p2\">](/windows/desktop/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-initializecriticalsectionandspincount)</ept> function indicates that the function applies to desktop apps only.","pos":[17888,18146],"source":" For example, the **Requirements** section of the documentation for the [InitializeCriticalSectionAndSpinCount](/windows/desktop/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-initializecriticalsectionandspincount) function indicates that the function applies to desktop apps only."},{"content":"In contrast, the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>InitializeCriticalSectionEx<ept id=\"p1\">](/windows/desktop/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-initializecriticalsectionex)</ept> function is available for both desktop apps and Windows Store apps.","pos":[18147,18332],"source":" In contrast, the [InitializeCriticalSectionEx](/windows/desktop/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-initializecriticalsectionex) function is available for both desktop apps and Windows Store apps."},{"content":"When developing your Profiler DLL, treat it as if it’s a Windows Store app and only use APIs that are documented as available to Windows Store apps.","pos":[18334,18482]},{"content":"Analyze your dependencies (for example, you can run <ph id=\"ph1\">`link /dump /imports`</ph> against your Profiler DLL to audit), and then search the docs to see which of your dependencies are ok and which aren’t.","pos":[18483,18677],"source":" Analyze your dependencies (for example, you can run `link /dump /imports` against your Profiler DLL to audit), and then search the docs to see which of your dependencies are ok and which aren’t."},{"content":"In most cases, your violations can be fixed by simply replacing them with a newer form of the API that is documented as safe (for example, replacing <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>InitializeCriticalSectionAndSpinCount<ept id=\"p1\">](/windows/desktop/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-initializecriticalsectionandspincount)</ept> with <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>InitializeCriticalSectionEx<ept id=\"p2\">](/windows/desktop/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-initializecriticalsectionex)</ept>).","pos":[18678,19055],"source":" In most cases, your violations can be fixed by simply replacing them with a newer form of the API that is documented as safe (for example, replacing [InitializeCriticalSectionAndSpinCount](/windows/desktop/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-initializecriticalsectionandspincount) with [InitializeCriticalSectionEx](/windows/desktop/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-initializecriticalsectionex))."},{"content":"You might notice that your Profiler DLL calls some APIs that apply to desktop apps only, and yet they seem to work even when your Profiler DLL is loaded inside a Windows Store app.","pos":[19057,19237]},{"content":"Be aware that it’s risky to use any API not documented for use with Windows Store apps in your Profiler DLL when loaded into a Windows Store app process:","pos":[19238,19391]},{"content":"Such APIs are not guaranteed to work when called in the unique context that Windows Store apps run in.","pos":[19395,19497]},{"content":"Such APIs might not work consistently when called from within different Windows Store app processes.","pos":[19501,19601]},{"content":"Such APIs might seem to work fine from Windows Store apps in the current version of Windows, but may break or be disabled in future releases of Windows.","pos":[19605,19757]},{"content":"The best advice is to fix all your violations and avoid the risk.","pos":[19759,19824]},{"content":"You might find that you absolutely cannot do without a particular API and cannot find a replacement suitable for Windows Store apps.","pos":[19826,19958]},{"content":"In such a case, at a minimum:","pos":[19959,19988]},{"content":"Test, test, test the living daylights out of your usage of that API.","pos":[19992,20060]},{"content":"Understand that the API might suddenly break or disappear if called from inside Windows Store apps in future releases of Windows.","pos":[20064,20193]},{"content":"This won’t be considered a compatibility concern by Microsoft, and supporting your usage of it will not be a priority.","pos":[20194,20312]},{"pos":[20318,20337],"content":"Reduced permissions","linkify":"Reduced permissions","nodes":[{"content":"Reduced permissions","pos":[0,19]}]},{"content":"It’s outside the scope of this topic to list all the ways that Windows Store app permissions differ from desktop apps.","pos":[20339,20457]},{"content":"But certainly the behavior will be different every time your Profiler DLL (when loaded into a Windows Store app as compared to a desktop app) tries to access any resources.","pos":[20458,20630]},{"content":"The file system is the most common example.","pos":[20631,20674]},{"content":"There are but a few places on disk that a given Windows Store app is allowed to access (see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>File access and permissions (Windows Runtime apps<ept id=\"p1\">](https://docs.microsoft.com/previous-versions/windows/apps/hh967755(v=win.10))</ept>), and your Profiler DLL will be under the same restrictions.","pos":[20675,20957],"source":" There are but a few places on disk that a given Windows Store app is allowed to access (see [File access and permissions (Windows Runtime apps](https://docs.microsoft.com/previous-versions/windows/apps/hh967755(v=win.10))), and your Profiler DLL will be under the same restrictions."},{"content":"Test your code thoroughly.","pos":[20958,20984]},{"pos":[20990,21017],"content":"Inter-process communication","linkify":"Inter-process communication","nodes":[{"content":"Inter-process communication","pos":[0,27]}]},{"content":"As shown in the diagram at the beginning of this paper, your Profiler DLL (loaded into the Windows Store app process space) will likely need to communicate with your Profiler UI (running in a separate desktop app process space) through your own custom inter-process communication (IPC) channel.","pos":[21019,21313]},{"content":"The Profiler UI sends signals to the Profiler DLL to modify its behavior, and the Profiler DLL sends data from the analyzed Windows Store app back to the Profiler UI for post-processing and displaying to the profiler user.","pos":[21314,21536]},{"content":"Most profilers need to work this way, but your choices for IPC mechanisms are more limited when your Profiler DLL is loaded into a Windows Store app.","pos":[21538,21687]},{"content":"For example, named pipes are not part of the Windows Store app SDK, so you cannot use them.","pos":[21688,21779]},{"content":"But of course, files are still in, albeit in a more limited fashion.","pos":[21781,21849]},{"content":"Events are also available.","pos":[21850,21876]},{"pos":[21878,21905],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Communicating via files<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>","source":"**Communicating via files**"},{"content":"Most of your data will likely pass between the Profiler DLL and Profiler UI via files.","pos":[21907,21993]},{"content":"The key is to pick a file location that both your Profiler DLL (in the context of a Windows Store app) and Profiler UI have read and write access to.","pos":[21994,22143]},{"content":"For example, the Temporary Folder path is a location that both your Profiler DLL and Profiler UI can access, but no other Windows Store app package can access (thus shielding any information you log from other Windows Store app packages).","pos":[22144,22382]},{"content":"Both your Profiler UI and Profiler DLL can determine this path independently.","pos":[22384,22461]},{"content":"Your Profiler UI, when it iterates through all packages installed for the current user (see the sample code earlier), gets access to the <ph id=\"ph1\">`PackageId`</ph> class, from which the Temporary Folder path can be derived with code similar to this snippet.","pos":[22462,22704],"source":" Your Profiler UI, when it iterates through all packages installed for the current user (see the sample code earlier), gets access to the `PackageId` class, from which the Temporary Folder path can be derived with code similar to this snippet."},{"content":"(As always, error checking is omitted for brevity.)","pos":[22705,22756]},{"pos":[22954,23195],"content":"Meanwhile, your Profiler DLL can do basically the same thing, though it can more easily get to the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:Windows.Storage.ApplicationData&gt;</ph> class by using the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>ApplicationData.Current<ept id=\"p1\">](xref:Windows.Storage.ApplicationData.Current%2A)</ept> property.","source":"Meanwhile, your Profiler DLL can do basically the same thing, though it can more easily get to the <xref:Windows.Storage.ApplicationData> class by using the [ApplicationData.Current](xref:Windows.Storage.ApplicationData.Current%2A) property."},{"pos":[23197,23225],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Communicating via events<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>","source":"**Communicating via events**"},{"content":"If you want simple signaling semantics between your Profiler UI and Profiler DLL, you can use events inside Windows Store apps as well as desktop apps.","pos":[23227,23378]},{"content":"From your Profiler DLL, you can simply call the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>CreateEventEx<ept id=\"p1\">](/windows/desktop/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-createeventexa)</ept> function to create a named event with any name you like.","pos":[23380,23558],"source":"From your Profiler DLL, you can simply call the [CreateEventEx](/windows/desktop/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-createeventexa) function to create a named event with any name you like."},{"content":"For example:","pos":[23559,23571]},{"content":"Your Profiler UI then needs to find that named event under the Windows Store app’s namespace.","pos":[23814,23907]},{"content":"For example, your Profiler UI could call <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>CreateEventEx<ept id=\"p1\">](/windows/desktop/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-createeventexa)</ept>, specifying the event name as","pos":[23908,24052],"source":" For example, your Profiler UI could call [CreateEventEx](/windows/desktop/api/synchapi/nf-synchapi-createeventexa), specifying the event name as"},{"content":"<ph id=\"ph1\">`&lt;acSid&gt;`</ph> is the Windows Store app’s AppContainer SID.","pos":[24103,24157],"source":"`<acSid>` is the Windows Store app’s AppContainer SID."},{"content":"An earlier section of this topic showed how to iterate over the packages installed for the current user.","pos":[24158,24262]},{"content":"From that sample code, you can obtain the packageId.","pos":[24263,24315]},{"content":"And from the packageId, you can obtain the <ph id=\"ph1\">`&lt;acSid&gt;`</ph> with code similar to the following:","pos":[24316,24404],"source":" And from the packageId, you can obtain the `<acSid>` with code similar to the following:"},{"pos":[24634,24659],"content":"No shutdown notifications","linkify":"No shutdown notifications","nodes":[{"content":"No shutdown notifications","pos":[0,25]}]},{"content":"When running inside a Windows Store app, your Profiler DLL should not rely on either <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>ICorProfilerCallback::Shutdown<ept id=\"p1\">](icorprofilercallback-shutdown-method.md)</ept> or even <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>DllMain<ept id=\"p2\">](/windows/desktop/Dlls/dllmain)</ept> (with <ph id=\"ph1\">`DLL_PROCESS_DETACH`</ph>) being called to notify your Profiler DLL that the Windows Store app is exiting.","pos":[24661,24976],"source":"When running inside a Windows Store app, your Profiler DLL should not rely on either [ICorProfilerCallback::Shutdown](icorprofilercallback-shutdown-method.md) or even [DllMain](/windows/desktop/Dlls/dllmain) (with `DLL_PROCESS_DETACH`) being called to notify your Profiler DLL that the Windows Store app is exiting."},{"content":"In fact, you should expect they will never be called.","pos":[24977,25030]},{"content":"Historically, many Profiler DLLs have used those notifications as convenient places to flush caches to disk, close files, send notifications back to the Profiler UI, etc. But now your Profiler DLL needs to be organized a little differently.","pos":[25031,25271]},{"content":"Your Profiler DLL should be logging information as it goes.","pos":[25273,25332]},{"content":"For performance reasons, you may want to batch information in memory and flush it to disk as the batch grows in size past some threshold.","pos":[25333,25470]},{"content":"But assume that any information not yet flushed to disk can be lost.","pos":[25471,25539]},{"content":"This means you’ll want to pick your threshold wisely, and that your Profiler UI needs to be hardened to deal with incomplete information written by the Profiler DLL.","pos":[25540,25705]},{"pos":[25710,25740],"content":"Windows Runtime metadata files","linkify":"Windows Runtime metadata files","nodes":[{"content":"Windows Runtime metadata files","pos":[0,30]}]},{"content":"It is outside the scope of this document to go into detail on what Windows Runtime metadata (WinMD) files are.","pos":[25742,25852]},{"content":"This section is limited to how the CLR Profiling API reacts when WinMD files are loaded by the Windows Store app your Profiler DLL is analyzing.","pos":[25853,25997]},{"pos":[26003,26033],"content":"Managed and non-managed WinMDs","linkify":"Managed and non-managed WinMDs","nodes":[{"content":"Managed and non-managed WinMDs","pos":[0,30]}]},{"content":"If a developer uses Visual Studio to create a new Windows Runtime Component project, a build of that project produces a WinMD file that describes the metadata (the type descriptions of classes, interfaces, etc.) authored by the developer.","pos":[26035,26273]},{"content":"If this project is a managed language project written in C# or VB, that same WinMD file also contains the implementation of those types (meaning that it contains all the IL compiled from the developer’s source code).","pos":[26274,26490]},{"content":"Such files are known as managed WinMD files.","pos":[26491,26535]},{"content":"They're interesting in that they contain both Windows Runtime metadata and the underlying implementation.","pos":[26536,26641]},{"content":"In contrast, if a developer creates a Windows Runtime Component project for C++, a build of that project produces a WinMD file that contains only metadata, and the implementation is compiled into a separate native DLL.","pos":[26643,26861]},{"content":"Similarly, the WinMD files that ship in the Windows SDK contain only metadata, with the implementation compiled into separate native DLLs that ship as part of Windows.","pos":[26862,27029]},{"content":"The information below applies to both managed WinMDs, which contain metadata and implementation, and to non-managed WinMDs, which contain only metadata.","pos":[27031,27183]},{"pos":[27189,27222],"content":"WinMD files look like CLR modules","linkify":"WinMD files look like CLR modules","nodes":[{"content":"WinMD files look like CLR modules","pos":[0,33]}]},{"content":"As far as the CLR is concerned, all WinMD files are modules.","pos":[27224,27284]},{"content":"The CLR Profiling API therefore tells your Profiler DLL when WinMD files load and what their ModuleIDs are, in the same way as for other managed modules.","pos":[27285,27438]},{"content":"Your Profiler DLL can distinguish WinMD files from other modules by calling the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>ICorProfilerInfo3::GetModuleInfo2<ept id=\"p1\">](icorprofilerinfo3-getmoduleinfo2-method.md)</ept> method and inspecting the <ph id=\"ph1\">`pdwModuleFlags`</ph> output parameter for the <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>COR_PRF_MODULE_WINDOWS_RUNTIME<ept id=\"p2\">](cor-prf-module-flags-enumeration.md)</ept> flag.","pos":[27440,27743],"source":"Your Profiler DLL can distinguish WinMD files from other modules by calling the [ICorProfilerInfo3::GetModuleInfo2](icorprofilerinfo3-getmoduleinfo2-method.md) method and inspecting the `pdwModuleFlags` output parameter for the [COR_PRF_MODULE_WINDOWS_RUNTIME](cor-prf-module-flags-enumeration.md) flag."},{"content":"(It’s set if and only if the ModuleID represents a WinMD.)","pos":[27744,27802]},{"pos":[27808,27836],"content":"Reading metadata from WinMDs","linkify":"Reading metadata from WinMDs","nodes":[{"content":"Reading metadata from WinMDs","pos":[0,28]}]},{"content":"WinMD files, like regular modules, contain metadata that can be read via the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Metadata APIs<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../../docs/framework/unmanaged-api/metadata/index.md)</ept>.","pos":[27838,27991],"source":"WinMD files, like regular modules, contain metadata that can be read via the [Metadata APIs](../../../../docs/framework/unmanaged-api/metadata/index.md)."},{"content":"However, the CLR maps Windows Runtime types to .NET Framework types when it reads WinMD files so that developers who program in managed code and consume the WinMD file can have a more natural programming experience.","pos":[27992,28207]},{"content":"For some examples of these mappings, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>.NET Framework Support for Windows Store Apps and Windows Runtime<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../../docs/standard/cross-platform/support-for-windows-store-apps-and-windows-runtime.md)</ept>.","pos":[28208,28413],"source":" For some examples of these mappings, see [.NET Framework Support for Windows Store Apps and Windows Runtime](../../../../docs/standard/cross-platform/support-for-windows-store-apps-and-windows-runtime.md)."},{"content":"So which view will your profiler get when it uses the metadata APIs: the raw Windows Runtime view, or the mapped .NET Framework view?","pos":[28415,28548]},{"content":"The answer: it’s up to you.","pos":[28550,28577]},{"content":"When you call the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>ICorProfilerInfo::GetModuleMetaData<ept id=\"p1\">](icorprofilerinfo-getmodulemetadata-method.md)</ept> method on a WinMD to obtain a metadata interface, such as <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>IMetaDataImport<ept id=\"p2\">](../../../../docs/framework/unmanaged-api/metadata/imetadataimport-interface.md)</ept>,  you can choose to set <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt>ofNoTransform<ept id=\"p3\">](../../../../docs/framework/unmanaged-api/metadata/coropenflags-enumeration.md)</ept> in the <ph id=\"ph1\">`dwOpenFlags`</ph> parameter to turn off this mapping.","pos":[28579,29012],"source":"When you call the [ICorProfilerInfo::GetModuleMetaData](icorprofilerinfo-getmodulemetadata-method.md) method on a WinMD to obtain a metadata interface, such as [IMetaDataImport](../../../../docs/framework/unmanaged-api/metadata/imetadataimport-interface.md),  you can choose to set [ofNoTransform](../../../../docs/framework/unmanaged-api/metadata/coropenflags-enumeration.md) in the `dwOpenFlags` parameter to turn off this mapping."},{"content":"Otherwise, by default, the mapping will be enabled.","pos":[29013,29064]},{"content":"Typically, a profiler will keep the mapping enabled, so that the strings that the Profiler DLL obtains from the WinMD metadata (for example, names of types) will look familiar and natural to the profiler user.","pos":[29065,29274]},{"pos":[29280,29310],"content":"Modifying metadata from WinMDs","linkify":"Modifying metadata from WinMDs","nodes":[{"content":"Modifying metadata from WinMDs","pos":[0,30]}]},{"content":"Modifying metadata in WinMDs is not supported.","pos":[29312,29358]},{"content":"If you call the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>ICorProfilerInfo::GetModuleMetaData<ept id=\"p1\">](icorprofilerinfo-getmodulemetadata-method.md)</ept> method for a WinMD file and specify <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>ofWrite<ept id=\"p2\">](../../../../docs/framework/unmanaged-api/metadata/coropenflags-enumeration.md)</ept> in the <ph id=\"ph1\">`dwOpenFlags`</ph> parameter or ask for a writeable metadata interface such as <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt>IMetaDataEmit<ept id=\"p3\">](../../../../docs/framework/unmanaged-api/metadata/imetadataemit-interface.md)</ept>, <bpt id=\"p4\">[</bpt>GetModuleMetaData<ept id=\"p4\">](icorprofilerinfo-getmodulemetadata-method.md)</ept> will fail.","pos":[29359,29836],"source":" If you call the [ICorProfilerInfo::GetModuleMetaData](icorprofilerinfo-getmodulemetadata-method.md) method for a WinMD file and specify [ofWrite](../../../../docs/framework/unmanaged-api/metadata/coropenflags-enumeration.md) in the `dwOpenFlags` parameter or ask for a writeable metadata interface such as [IMetaDataEmit](../../../../docs/framework/unmanaged-api/metadata/imetadataemit-interface.md), [GetModuleMetaData](icorprofilerinfo-getmodulemetadata-method.md) will fail."},{"content":"This is of particular importance to IL-rewriting profilers, which need to modify metadata to support their instrumentation (for example, to add AssemblyRefs or new methods).","pos":[29837,30010]},{"content":"So you should check for <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>COR_PRF_MODULE_WINDOWS_RUNTIME<ept id=\"p1\">](cor-prf-module-flags-enumeration.md)</ept> first (as discussed in the previous section) and refrain from asking for writeable metadata interfaces on such modules.","pos":[30011,30224],"source":" So you should check for [COR_PRF_MODULE_WINDOWS_RUNTIME](cor-prf-module-flags-enumeration.md) first (as discussed in the previous section) and refrain from asking for writeable metadata interfaces on such modules."},{"pos":[30230,30271],"content":"Resolving assembly references with WinMDs","linkify":"Resolving assembly references with WinMDs","nodes":[{"content":"Resolving assembly references with WinMDs","pos":[0,41]}]},{"content":"Many profilers need to resolve metadata references manually to aid with instrumentation or type inspection.","pos":[30273,30380]},{"content":"Such profilers need to be aware of how the CLR resolves assembly references that point to WinMDs, because those references are resolved in a completely different way than standard assembly references.","pos":[30381,30581]},{"pos":[30586,30602],"content":"Memory profilers","linkify":"Memory profilers","nodes":[{"content":"Memory profilers","pos":[0,16]}]},{"content":"The garbage collector and managed heap are not fundamentally different in a Windows Store app and a desktop app.","pos":[30604,30716]},{"content":"However, there are some subtle differences that profiler authors need to be aware of.","pos":[30717,30802]},{"pos":[30808,30840],"content":"ForceGC creates a managed thread","linkify":"ForceGC creates a managed thread","nodes":[{"content":"ForceGC creates a managed thread","pos":[0,32]}]},{"content":"When doing memory profiling, your Profiler DLL typically creates a separate thread from which to call the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>ForceGC Method<ept id=\"p1\">](icorprofilerinfo-forcegc-method.md)</ept> method.","pos":[30842,31008],"source":"When doing memory profiling, your Profiler DLL typically creates a separate thread from which to call the [ForceGC Method](icorprofilerinfo-forcegc-method.md) method."},{"content":"This is nothing new.","pos":[31009,31029]},{"content":"But what might be surprising is that the act of doing a garbage collection inside a Windows Store app may transform your thread into a managed thread (for example, a Profiling API ThreadID will be created for that thread).","pos":[31030,31252]},{"content":"To understand the consequences of this, it’s important to understand the differences between synchronous and asynchronous calls as defined by the CLR Profiling API.","pos":[31254,31418]},{"content":"Note that this is very different from the concept of asynchronous calls in Windows Store apps.","pos":[31419,31513]},{"content":"See the blog post <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Why we have CORPROF_E_UNSUPPORTED_CALL_SEQUENCE<ept id=\"p1\">](https://blogs.msdn.microsoft.com/davbr/2008/12/23/why-we-have-corprof_e_unsupported_call_sequence/)</ept> for more information.","pos":[31514,31703],"source":" See the blog post [Why we have CORPROF_E_UNSUPPORTED_CALL_SEQUENCE](https://blogs.msdn.microsoft.com/davbr/2008/12/23/why-we-have-corprof_e_unsupported_call_sequence/) for more information."},{"content":"The relevant point is that calls made on threads created by your profiler are always considered synchronous, even if those calls are made from outside an implementation of one of your Profiler DLL’s <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>ICorProfilerCallback<ept id=\"p1\">](icorprofilercallback-interface.md)</ept> methods.","pos":[31705,31970],"source":"The relevant point is that calls made on threads created by your profiler are always considered synchronous, even if those calls are made from outside an implementation of one of your Profiler DLL’s [ICorProfilerCallback](icorprofilercallback-interface.md) methods."},{"content":"At least, that used to be the case.","pos":[31971,32006]},{"content":"Now that the CLR has turned your profiler’s thread into a managed thread because of your call to <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>ForceGC Method<ept id=\"p1\">](icorprofilerinfo-forcegc-method.md)</ept>, that thread is no longer considered your profiler’s thread.","pos":[32007,32217],"source":" Now that the CLR has turned your profiler’s thread into a managed thread because of your call to [ForceGC Method](icorprofilerinfo-forcegc-method.md), that thread is no longer considered your profiler’s thread."},{"content":"As such, the CLR enforces a more stringent definition of what qualifies as synchronous for that thread—namely that a call must originate from inside one of your Profiler DLL’s <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>ICorProfilerCallback<ept id=\"p1\">](icorprofilercallback-interface.md)</ept> methods to qualify as synchronous.","pos":[32218,32486],"source":" As such, the CLR enforces a more stringent definition of what qualifies as synchronous for that thread—namely that a call must originate from inside one of your Profiler DLL’s [ICorProfilerCallback](icorprofilercallback-interface.md) methods to qualify as synchronous."},{"content":"What does this mean in practice?","pos":[32488,32520]},{"content":"Most <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>ICorProfilerInfo<ept id=\"p1\">](icorprofilerinfo-interface.md)</ept> methods are only safe to be called synchronously, and will immediately fail otherwise.","pos":[32521,32662],"source":" Most [ICorProfilerInfo](icorprofilerinfo-interface.md) methods are only safe to be called synchronously, and will immediately fail otherwise."},{"content":"So if your Profiler DLL reuses your <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>ForceGC Method<ept id=\"p1\">](icorprofilerinfo-forcegc-method.md)</ept> thread for other calls typically made on profiler-created threads (for example, to <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>RequestProfilerDetach<ept id=\"p2\">](icorprofilerinfo3-requestprofilerdetach-method.md)</ept>, <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt>RequestReJIT<ept id=\"p3\">](icorprofilerinfo4-requestrejit-method.md)</ept>, or <bpt id=\"p4\">[</bpt>RequestRevert<ept id=\"p4\">](icorprofilerinfo4-requestrevert-method.md)</ept>), you’re going to have trouble.","pos":[32663,33062],"source":" So if your Profiler DLL reuses your [ForceGC Method](icorprofilerinfo-forcegc-method.md) thread for other calls typically made on profiler-created threads (for example, to [RequestProfilerDetach](icorprofilerinfo3-requestprofilerdetach-method.md), [RequestReJIT](icorprofilerinfo4-requestrejit-method.md), or [RequestRevert](icorprofilerinfo4-requestrevert-method.md)), you’re going to have trouble."},{"content":"Even an asynchronous-safe function such as <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>DoStackSnapshot<ept id=\"p1\">](icorprofilerinfo2-dostacksnapshot-method.md)</ept> has special rules when called from managed threads.","pos":[33063,33220],"source":" Even an asynchronous-safe function such as [DoStackSnapshot](icorprofilerinfo2-dostacksnapshot-method.md) has special rules when called from managed threads."},{"content":"(See the blog post <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Profiler stack walking: Basics and beyond<ept id=\"p1\">](https://blogs.msdn.microsoft.com/davbr/2005/10/06/profiler-stack-walking-basics-and-beyond/)</ept> for more information.)","pos":[33221,33399],"source":" (See the blog post [Profiler stack walking: Basics and beyond](https://blogs.msdn.microsoft.com/davbr/2005/10/06/profiler-stack-walking-basics-and-beyond/) for more information.)"},{"content":"Therefore, we recommend that any thread your Profiler DLL creates to call <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>ForceGC Method<ept id=\"p1\">](icorprofilerinfo-forcegc-method.md)</ept> should be used <bpt id=\"p2\">*</bpt>only<ept id=\"p2\">*</ept> for the purpose of triggering GCs and then responding to the GC callbacks.","pos":[33401,33624],"source":"Therefore, we recommend that any thread your Profiler DLL creates to call [ForceGC Method](icorprofilerinfo-forcegc-method.md) should be used *only* for the purpose of triggering GCs and then responding to the GC callbacks."},{"content":"It should not call into the Profiling API to perform other tasks like stack sampling or detaching.","pos":[33625,33723]},{"pos":[33729,33759],"content":"ConditionalWeakTableReferences","linkify":"ConditionalWeakTableReferences","nodes":[{"content":"ConditionalWeakTableReferences","pos":[0,30]}]},{"content":"Starting with the .NET Framework 4.5, there is a new GC callback, <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>ConditionalWeakTableElementReferences<ept id=\"p1\">](icorprofilercallback5-conditionalweaktableelementreferences-method.md)</ept>, which gives the profiler more complete information about <bpt id=\"p2\">*</bpt>dependent handles<ept id=\"p2\">*</ept>.","pos":[33761,34016],"source":"Starting with the .NET Framework 4.5, there is a new GC callback, [ConditionalWeakTableElementReferences](icorprofilercallback5-conditionalweaktableelementreferences-method.md), which gives the profiler more complete information about *dependent handles*."},{"content":"These handles effectively add a reference from a source object to a target object for the purpose of GC lifetime management.","pos":[34017,34141]},{"content":"Dependent handles are nothing new, and developers who program in managed code have been able to create their own dependent handles by using the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Runtime.CompilerServices.ConditionalWeakTable%602?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> class even before Windows 8 and the .NET Framework 4.5.","pos":[34142,34434],"source":" Dependent handles are nothing new, and developers who program in managed code have been able to create their own dependent handles by using the <xref:System.Runtime.CompilerServices.ConditionalWeakTable%602?displayProperty=nameWithType> class even before Windows 8 and the .NET Framework 4.5."},{"content":"However, managed XAML Windows Store apps now make heavy use of dependent handles.","pos":[34436,34517]},{"content":"In particular, the CLR uses them to aid with managing reference cycles between managed objects and unmanaged Windows Runtime objects.","pos":[34518,34651]},{"content":"This means that it’s more important now than ever for memory profilers to be informed of these dependent handles so that they can be visualized along with the rest of the edges in the heap graph.","pos":[34652,34847]},{"content":"Your Profiler DLL should use <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>RootReferences2<ept id=\"p1\">](icorprofilercallback2-rootreferences2-method.md)</ept>, <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>ObjectReferences<ept id=\"p2\">](icorprofilercallback-objectreferences-method.md)</ept>, and <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt>ConditionalWeakTableElementReferences<ept id=\"p3\">](icorprofilercallback5-conditionalweaktableelementreferences-method.md)</ept> together to form a complete view of the heap graph.","pos":[34848,35180],"source":" Your Profiler DLL should use [RootReferences2](icorprofilercallback2-rootreferences2-method.md), [ObjectReferences](icorprofilercallback-objectreferences-method.md), and [ConditionalWeakTableElementReferences](icorprofilercallback5-conditionalweaktableelementreferences-method.md) together to form a complete view of the heap graph."},{"pos":[35185,35195],"content":"Conclusion","linkify":"Conclusion","nodes":[{"content":"Conclusion","pos":[0,10]}]},{"content":"It is possible to use the CLR Profiling API to analyze managed code running inside Windows Store apps.","pos":[35197,35299]},{"content":"In fact, you can take an existing profiler that you’re developing and make some specific changes so that it can target Windows Store apps.","pos":[35300,35438]},{"content":"Your Profiler UI should use the new APIs for activating the Windows Store app in debugging mode.","pos":[35439,35535]},{"content":"Make sure that your Profiler DLL consumes only those APIs applicable for Windows Store apps.","pos":[35536,35628]},{"content":"The communication mechanism between your Profiler DLL and Profiler UI should be written with the Windows Store app API restrictions in mind and with awareness of the restricted permissions in place for Windows Store apps.","pos":[35629,35850]},{"content":"Your Profiler DLL should be aware of how the CLR treats WinMDs, and how the Garbage Collector’s behavior is different with respect to managed threads.","pos":[35851,36001]},{"pos":[36006,36015],"content":"Resources","linkify":"Resources","nodes":[{"content":"Resources","pos":[0,9]}]},{"pos":[36017,36048],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>The Common Language Runtime<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>","source":"**The Common Language Runtime**"},{"pos":[36052,36099],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Profiling (Unmanaged API Reference)<ept id=\"p1\">](index.md)</ept>","source":"[Profiling (Unmanaged API Reference)](index.md)"},{"pos":[36103,36161],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Metadata (Unmanaged API Reference)<ept id=\"p1\">](../metadata/index.md)</ept>","source":"[Metadata (Unmanaged API Reference)](../metadata/index.md)"},{"pos":[36163,36213],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>The CLR's interaction with the Windows Runtime<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>","source":"**The CLR's interaction with the Windows Runtime**"},{"pos":[36217,36380],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>.NET Framework Support for Windows Store Apps and Windows Runtime<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../../docs/standard/cross-platform/support-for-windows-store-apps-and-windows-runtime.md)</ept>","source":"[.NET Framework Support for Windows Store Apps and Windows Runtime](../../../../docs/standard/cross-platform/support-for-windows-store-apps-and-windows-runtime.md)"},{"pos":[36382,36404],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Windows Store apps<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>","source":"**Windows Store apps**"},{"pos":[36408,36541],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>File access and permissions (Windows Runtime apps<ept id=\"p1\">](https://docs.microsoft.com/previous-versions/windows/apps/hh967755%28v=win.10%29)</ept>","source":"[File access and permissions (Windows Runtime apps](https://docs.microsoft.com/previous-versions/windows/apps/hh967755%28v=win.10%29)"},{"pos":[36545,36652],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Get a developer license<ept id=\"p1\">](https://docs.microsoft.com/previous-versions/windows/apps/hh974578%28v=win.10%29)</ept>","source":"[Get a developer license](https://docs.microsoft.com/previous-versions/windows/apps/hh974578%28v=win.10%29)"},{"pos":[36656,36764],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>IPackageDebugSettings Interface<ept id=\"p1\">](/windows/desktop/api/shobjidl_core/nn-shobjidl_core-ipackagedebugsettings)</ept>","source":"[IPackageDebugSettings Interface](/windows/desktop/api/shobjidl_core/nn-shobjidl_core-ipackagedebugsettings)"}]}